  "title": "Oxidation number",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Oxidation number for some imp compounds",
      "conceptBody": "<p><strong>For Example</strong></p><p>(1) O.N. of nitrogen in $\\text{HN}{{\\text{O}}_{3}},\\text{NaN}{{\\text{O}}_{3}},\\text{Ca}{{\\left( \\text{N}{{\\text{O}}_{3}} \\right)}_{2}}$ is same, i.e. +5 .</p><p>(2) O.N. of sulphur in ${{\\text{H}}_{2}}~\\text{S},\\text{CaS},\\text{N}{{\\text{a}}_{2}}~\\text{S }\\!\\!\\And\\!\\!\\text{ A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}~{{\\text{S}}_{3}}$ is equal.</p><p>(3) Oxidation number of a metal in carbonyl complex is always zero.</p><p>e.g. $\\text{Fe}$ in $\\text{Fe}{{(\\text{CO})}_{5}}$</p><p>$\\text{Ni}$ in $\\text{Ni}{{(\\text{CO})}_{4}}$</p><p>Here the O.N. of CO is taken to be zero.</p><p>(4) Oxidation number can be zero, + ve, – ve (integer or fraction). e.g. O.N. of $\\text{O}$ in $\\text{K}{{\\text{O}}_{2}}$ is $-1/2$</p><p>(5) Maximum O.N. of an element is = Group No.</p><p>(Except O &amp; F)</p><p>(6) Minimum O.N. of an element = Group No. –8</p><p>(Except metals)</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcd5c03b9dcaf1afe7e7"
    },
    {
      "title": "Oxidation number for Peroxide linkage",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>&nbsp;<strong>Special Method</strong></h3><p>{If we do not know the number of peroxide linkages}</p><p>(1) Oxidation no. ${{\\mathbf{H}}_{2}}\\mathbf{S}{{\\mathbf{O}}_{5}}$ (Caro’s Acid)</p><p>If $\\text{a}$ is the no. of peroxy linkages.</p><p>$\\therefore \\quad $ No. of ${{\\text{O}}^{-}}$atoms attached to peroxy linkage $=2\\text{a}$</p><p>O.N. of peroxy linkage $=-1$</p><p>Let $x$ be the oxidation no. of $\\text{S}$</p><p>$2\\,\\,1+\\text{x}+(5-2\\text{a})\\text{ }(-2)+2\\text{a}(-1)=0$</p><p>$2+\\text{x}-2\\text{a}-10+4\\text{a }=0$</p><p>$\\text{x}+2\\text{a }=8$</p><p>$\\text{a }=1$</p><p>$\\text{x }=+6$</p><p>Peroxy linkage is formed at maximum of electronegative atom</p><p>(2) ${{\\mathbf{H}}_{2}}{{\\mathbf{S}}_{2}}{{\\mathbf{O}}_{\\mathbf{8}}}$</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p>$2\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,1+2\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,x+(\\text{za})(-1)+(8-2\\text{a})(-2)=0$</p><p>$2+2\\text{x}-2\\text{a}-16+4\\text{a }=0$</p><p>$2\\text{x}+2\\text{a }=14$</p><p>$\\text{x}+\\text{a }=7$</p><p>$\\text{a }=1$</p><p>$\\text{x }=6$</p></td><td><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>The compounds containing element which have highest oxidation state always act as oxidant.</p><p>Example $\\overset{+5}{\\mathop{\\text{HN}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}}}\\,,~\\,\\,{{\\text{K}}_{2}}\\overset{+6}{\\mathop{\\text{C}{{\\text{r}}_{2}}}}\\,{{\\text{O}}_{7}},\\,\\,\\,\\overset{+7}{\\mathop{\\text{KMn}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}}}\\,,\\overset{+7}{\\mathop{\\,\\,~\\text{KCl}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}}}\\,$</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcd5c03b9dcaf1afe7e8"
    }
